  "articleSummary": "**Summary:**\n\n\"Into the Breach\" argues that the traditional security model—treat production as dangerous, treat local development as safe—is dead. Developer machines have become \"credential warehouses\" containing tokens, keys, and secrets that attackers target through AI prompts, poisoned packages, and infostealers. The author frames \"be careful\" advice as a failed non-solution and instead advocates for technical boundaries: isolated Dev Containers, strategically deployed canary tokens (fake secrets that alert when touched), limited filesystem mounts, and delayed dependency updates. The piece is a passionate, practical security guide mixing dark humor (attackers \"found old keys in a desk drawer\") with actionable configuration snippets. Intended audience is software developers and Dev",
